Create a function to get the mRNA per gene and exons per mRNA

"collectRelationships" <- function(gff, dataset.name="X"){
  IDs <- getGffAttribute(gff,"ID")
  p.list <- strsplit(getGffAttribute(gff,"Parent"),",")
  typs <- rep(gff$type,elementLengths(p.list))
  Parents <- unlist(p.list)
  
  mRNA=as.integer(table(Parents[typs %in% c("mRNA","tRNA")][Parents[typs %in% c("mRNA","tRNA")] %in% IDs[gff$type=="gene"]]))
  exon=as.integer(table(Parents[typs=="exon"][Parents[typs=="exon"] %in% IDs[gff$type %in% c("mRNA","tRNA")]]))
  stopifnot(sum(mRNA)==length(exon))
  
  return(data.frame(Dataset=dataset.name,
                    Feature=rep(c("mRNA","exon"),
                                c(length(mRNA),
                                  length(exon))),
                    Number=c(mRNA,exon)))
}

"collectSizes" <- function(gff,dataset.name="X"){
  
  ## get the introns 
  ex.sel <- gff$type=="exon"
  p.list <- strsplit(getGffAttribute(gff[ex.sel,],"Parent"),",")
  Parents <- unlist(p.list)
  grng <- sort(GRanges(seqnames = Parents,
                       ranges = IRanges(
                         rep(gff[ex.sel,1],elementLengths(p.list)),
                         rep(gff[ex.sel,2],elementLengths(p.list))),
                       scf = rep(seq_name(gff[ex.sel,]),elementLengths(p.list))
  ))
  starts <- start(grng)[match(unique(Parents),Parents)]  
  names(starts) <- unique(Parents)
  intron.grng <- gaps(grng,start=starts)
  ## de-duplicate (remove exact coordinates dups)
  ## we do not use the strand as gaps is an unstranded method
  intron.dup <- duplicated(paste(
    grng$scf[match(as.character(seqnames(intron.grng)),
                   as.character(seqnames(grng)))],
    start(intron.grng),
    end(intron.grng),sep="_"))
  intron <- width(intron.grng)[!intron.dup]
  
  ## For the rest of the features, ignore duplicates!
  dups <- duplicated(paste(seq_name(gff),
                           gff[,1],
                           gff[,2],
                           gff$type,
                           gff$strand,sep="_"))
  gff <- gff[!dups,]
  
  # get all sizes
  sizes <- gff[,2] - gff[,1] + 1
  
  # return a data.frame (melted for ggplots2)
  return(data.frame(Dataset=dataset.name,
                    Length=c(sizes,intron),
                    Feature=c(as.character(gff$type),rep("intron",length(intron))))
  )
}

Perform the VST

colData(dds)$condition <- factor(colData(dds)$condition,
                                 levels=unique(conditions))
vsd <- varianceStabilizingTransformation(dds, blind=TRUE, fitType="local")
vst <- assay(vsd)
colnames(vst) <- colnames(count.table)
vst <- vst - min(vst)

4 Updates

4.1 Events

Summarize the type of events:

  • stable: gene structure stable
  • split: gene structure split into 2 genes
  • merged: several gene structures merged into one
  • merged.as.sv: a subset of the above, where different splice variants where also introduced
  • novel: novel gene structure
  • duplicate: a subset of the above, when the same gene was detected through different supporting evidences
  • antisense: a subset of novel, where a gene was reported on the antisense strand
dfs <- mclapply(dir(pattern="\\.csv$"),read.csv,row.names=1,
                stringsAsFactors=FALSE,mc.cores=12)
names(dfs) <- sub("first-iteration","V1",
                  sub("second-iteration","V2",
                      tolower(gsub("Potra01|\\.gene_structures_post_PASA_|-validated-updates\\.csv","",dir(pattern="\\.csv$")))))

events <- sapply(lapply(lapply(dfs,"[[","status"),factor,
                        levels=c("antisense","duplicate","merged","merged.as.sv","novel","split","stable")),table)

orig.gene <- gffs[["Potra01"]][gffs[["Potra01"]]$type=="gene",]

We have had one ID swap between two genes, so we skip those although they were conserved for the calcuation below

keep <- which(strand(orig.gene) == strand(final.gene))

4.2 ID evolution

Flatten the dfs into a list of edges

edge.list <- do.call(rbind,lapply(dfs,"[",c("oldID","newID")))

Remove self-edges

edge.list <- edge.list[edge.list$oldID != edge.list$newID,]

create the graph

graf <- graph.edgelist(as.matrix(edge.list))

And look at its properties.

Most ID change once, but a few change more often (up to 6 times!)

barplot(table(clusters(graf)$csize),las=2,log="y")

Check that subgraph

baron <- induced.subgraph(graf,v=vertex.attributes(graf)$name[which(clusters(graf)$membership == which.max(clusters(graf)$csize))])

It involves the following IDs

get.vertex.attribute(graf,"name")[which(clusters(graf)$membership == which.max(clusters(graf)$csize))]

check the only one with a connectivity of 4 A 4 way merge

baron <- induced.subgraph(graf,v=vertex.attributes(graf)$name[which(clusters(graf)$membership %in% which(clusters(graf)$csize == 5) )])
b.edges <- get.edgelist(baron)
tab <- table(as.vector(b.edges))
baron <- induced.subgraph(graf,v=unique(as.vector(b.edges[rowSums(b.edges == names(tab[tab==4]))>0,])))
plot.igraph(baron,layout=layout.kamada.kawai,vertex.size=1)
